Hey there

My name is Sam Granger. I'm a front end web developer whose sites and elements help people tell stories, have insights, and make connections.

When I'm not working or thinking (or thinking about thinking), I'm usually playing guitar, learning a new language, or spending time in the woods and waters of my home state of Michigan.

I'm always looking for new problems to solve, new projects to take on, and new people to meet. So take a look around and let's get in touch.

How I Work

Most days you'll find me revamping someone's Wordpress site, coding up some custom features, or building a site from the ground up. Logic and creativity not only influence my code, they drive my life. I'm like my code: clean, logical, and fun to interact with.

Taking a vision from sketches on paper to pixels on screen is my joy. The problem solving along the way is my creative process.

I've always been a jack of all trades and master of some. And I bring to web development a vision I gained through my background in photography, illustration, publishing, and film.

Here's a handful of images that help you see how I often look at the world. If you'd like to see a portfolio or case study, get a hold of me.

Design & Code

The Odyssey

A passion project of mine is an interactive interlinear version of Homer's Odyssey. Read it in Greek or English or toggle between the two. .
Full site coming soon.

DavenFund

Davenport University needed a little social network for their DavenFund initiative. Employees submit proposals for funds to make their work environment better. They can also view the proposals submitted by others. Launched February 2017.
I'd give you a link, but it's employees only. If you want to see some more of it, get a hold of me.

This Site

Hope you like what you see. This site was coded from the ground up. Main features are Jekyll templating, some custom SVG animations, and a fairly extensive Sass architecture. Check out the source on GitHub.

Madcap Coffee

Madcap Coffee is an award-winning roastery located in Grand Rapids, MI. This site was designed by Conduit Studios. I was brought on board with the CurlyHost development team.
The majority of my work was developing responsive templates and plugins that were intuitive for both visitors to experience and the client to use. Some of my favorite projects were keeping backgrounds lined up with bag labels, custom gradients, generating related products and slideshows on the fly, and responsively dealing with overflow text.

Spicy Reads

Ed Spicer is a retired teacher, a bibliophile, and an old friend. He needed a new site that could direct people to his critical work on children's literature.
